nism rooted in religion and imperialism.Gale L. Kenny examines this Christian imperial feminism from the women’s missionary movement tocreate a Christian world order. She shows that this Christian imperial feminism marked a break from anearlier Protestant world view that focused on moral and racial purity and in which interactions amongraces were inconceivable. This new approach actually prioritized issues like civil rights and racialintegration, as well as the uplift of women, though the racially diverse world Christianity it aspired towas still to be rigidly hierarchically ordered, with white women retaining a privileged place as guardians.In exposing these dynamics, this book departs from recent scholarship on white evangelical nationalismto focus on the racial politics of white religious liberalism. Christian Imperial Feminism adds a necessarylayer to our understanding of religion, gender, and empire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChristian womenxPolitical activityzUnited States2DLC. 0aChristian womenxPolitical activityzUnited States. 0aChristian womenxReligious lifezUnited States2DLC. 0aChristian womenxReligious lifezUnited States. 0aChristianity and politicszUnited States2DLC. 0aChristianity and politicszUnited States. 0aFeminismxReligious aspects2DLC. 0aProselytizing2DLC. 0aProtestant churcheszUnites StatesxInfluence2DLC. 0aRacexReligious aspects2DLC. 0aWomen missionarieszUnited states2DLC. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Protestant.2bisacsh  aChurch Woman's Committee on Race Relations.  aChurch Women United.  aCouncil of Women for Home Missions.  aFederation of Woman's Boards of Foreign Missions.  aHelen Barrett Montgomery.  aProtestant Feminism.  aProtestant women.  aUnited Council of Church Women.  aYWCA.  abooks about religion and feminism.  ab